<TITLE> BCL activist killed in capital </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 12 (bdnews24.com)  A senior pro-government student activist was shot and killed by unknown assailants in the capital on Friday. Home minister Sahara Khatun paid a visit at the medical college and told reporters there that these were all bids to destabilise the country. "The matter will be investigated further." ABM Faruk, 33, president of Cantonment Thana chapter and also head of Ward 15 unit, was shot at around 9:30pm. Russell, a youth who had carried Faruk's body, said climed over the walls of the playground of Manikdi Adorsho Biddyaniketan upon hearing gunshots. The gates to the playground were locked since school was out for the day. Russell told bdnews24.com that when a few of the youths found Faruk critically wounded inside the compound near Dhaka Canotoment. Deputy police commissioner of Gulshan, Hafiz Akhter told bdnews24.com that uknown assailants shot and killed Faruk at the school playground. Witnesses said Faruk's body bore at least nine gunshot wounds. His brother ABM Qamrul Hasan said he had come out of the house hearing gunshots. "We were told that Faruk had been shot. By the time we got to the mecial college, he was dead." He did not name any possible suspects. Faruk was taken to the Dhaka Medical College Hospital in a critical state and underwent surgery. At around 11:00pm, doctors declared him dead. Sahara Khatun said these were part of a ploy to create instability in the country. "We all know very well who they are." When asked about the visibly deteriorating law and order situation, which she had claimed was improving only a few days ago, Sahara said that the situation was actually improving throughout last year. "But a certain quarter is causing it to deteriorate." Central general secretary of Bangladesh Chhatra League, the student wing of the ruling Awami League, Mahfuzul Haider Chowdhury Roton claimed that Jamaat-e-Islami and its student wing Islami Chhatra Shibir were involved in the killing. He demanded that the government ban the Shibir and Jamaat, a fundamentalist party, which is a major ally of main opposition BNP. bd
